segments.text: nice pants or blue jeans or things like that and look nice, well, I think they're fine.
But I don't like these slouchy ones that just anything's all right because nowadays people wear pants.
I went to the doctor's office in Houston with my sister the other day, and honey, you just wouldn't realize the people came in there dressed like they did.
There was about four of us in that office, and it was full that were dressed decent.
And the rest of them wear the slouchiest things.
They just wear any kind of old sandals.
Some of them wear their house shoes.
House shoes, my God.
That's going a little too far.
That's true.
And they just don't dress like they should for young girls, I don't think.
Now, as far as pants, I'm all for them.
I think they're nice when they're nice and clean and all.
And I do like them.
But I do not like them.
People just take for granted, well, everybody wears pants.
Well, I can just stick on anything.
Tie your shirt tail around your stomach and go on.
They think that's all right, but I don't.
I just don't think we ought to do that, not out in public.
Mrs. Presnell, what kind of entertainment did y'all have when y'all were younger?
Well, in those days, you see, we had no cars or anything like that, so we went on foot or horseback or something like that.
So we just had our entertainment around in the neighborhood, and we had what they called play parties.
It's kind of like square dancing.
And we made the music ourselves.
We sang instead of having them.
Y'all didn't have any instruments to play?
No, we sang as we played.
So then...
We would meet at the homes and have singings, religious songs.
Whoever had organ or piano in the home, that's where we'd meet.
And we always did that lots of times, maybe once a week.
And then we had ice cream suppers.
My daddy was always big on giving ice cream supper for all the people in the community.
And everybody would come and bring homemade ice cream.
I love homemade ice cream.
Everybody would make cakes, and everybody pitched in and brought stuff.
But we really had a good time when we had those big ice cream
suppers.
And we always, and when we have those parties, you know those days in the community you had no place for recreation or anything.
That's right.
But we'd just take a bedroom, we'd take everything out of that bedroom and store it somewhere else and just clean that room out and that's where we had our party in that room.
And then when it was over with, of course, it all had to be put back.
But still, it was lots of fun, and it was good, clean fun.
And I'll never forget one night.
Go ahead.
I went to a party, and I really liked this boy.
It was the first boy I ever had.
And somebody had their violin there, and they got to playing the violin.
And he came over and asked me, he said, won't you come on and dance with me?
I said, I can't.
He said, oh, you can.
I said, no, I can't.
I said, I wouldn't get home before Papa would know it.
And he didn't let us dance now.
Papa didn't.
He didn't believe in it.
We could go to these play parties and make our own music, but we didn't dance by other music.
So I just couldn't turn him down.
So I got up and danced with him.
But Papa knew it before I got home.
And I didn't go anywhere for a month.
We were penalized when we did things that we knew that we shouldn't do.
And, of course, I didn't see any harm in it.
And I said, well, it was worth it to get to dance with him.
Because you liked him, right?
Yeah, I really did.
Well, did y'all ride?
I mean, was a lot of y'all do horseback riding?
Yeah, we did lots of horseback riding.
Did y'all play games on horses?
Like, my mother used to do that.
No, I don't think we did.
And we used to play basketball.
We'd meet on Sunday and play basketball.
We'd play baseball, things like that.
Boys and girls all played together and just had a big time.
And we just...
I'll never forget one time, another girl and I were going somewhere horseback.
And I was riding a horse that belonged to my brother.
And she wouldn't let nobody outrun her.
Now, no horse was going to outrun her.
And we was just trotting along, and she thought we was fixing her.
This other horse was going to outrun her.
And she took off down through that winding road through the woods.
And I'm going to tell you, I just did stay on.
I'd like to never stopped her.
She was crazy as she could be.
And finally.
Her coat was the cause of this boy that I liked so well's death.
She ran into a tree with him and killed him.
The horse?
The horse's coat was.
We had sold her to him.
My brother had sold him to him, and this horse ran into a tree.
He was racing him.
And how do you say how he could run into a tree?
He just didn't look?
I don't know how come.
I don't know anything about it.
The horse must have been blind.
That's what happened.
It just killed him.
He died just a day or so.
It's too bad.
Mm-hmm.
So that was the kind of entertainment we had.
It was good coon fun.
We enjoyed it.
Because that's all we knew.
We didn't have picture shows to go to.
Well, we didn't have transportation to go to picture shows.
No television either.
No, we didn't have no television.
No radio?
No.
The only way was we'd have these Edison record players, you know, that you wind up.
We had one of those.
Had lots of records for that.
We enjoyed that a lot.
And I'd give anything now if I had that.
I bet you would.
Anybody would.
It's antique right now.
It used to cylinder type records, you know.
It had a big horn on it.
Yeah.
We have one at the house.
I just wonder sometimes why they went with it.
The one we went with, my mother's got one at the house.
But it's not the wind-up.
It has a horn.
It was real pretty.
